SIMPLE: tryst
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tryst
<hw>Tryst</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>trist</ets>,
<ets>tryst</ets>, a variant of <ets>trust</ets>; cf. Icel.
<ets>treysta</ets> to make trusty, fr. <ets>traust</ets> confidence,
security. See <er>Trust</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Trust.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An appointment to meet; also, an appointed place or
time of meeting; <as>as, to keep <ex>tryst</ex>; to break
<ex>tryst</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Scot. or Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To bide tryst</b></col>, <cd>to wait, at the appointed
time, for one with whom a tryst or engagement is made; to keep an
engagement or appointment.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The tenderest-hearted maid⟦br⟧
That ever <qex>bided tryst</qex> at village stile.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tryst</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tryst
<hw>Tryst</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>tristen</ets>,
<ets>trysten</ets>. See <er>Tryst</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To trust.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To agree with to meet at a certain place; to make an
appointment with.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>
<rj><au>Burns.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tryst</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tryst
<hw>Tryst</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To mutually agree to meet at a
certain place.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tryster</ent>⟦br⟧
